1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074
Someone needs to stop Clearway Law.
Public shouldn't leave reviews for lawyers.

2
00:04:22,300 --> 00:04:23,700
Saigon.

3
00:04:25,470 --> 00:04:26,470
Shit.

4
00:04:28,598 --> 00:04:30,557
I'm still only in Saigon.

5
00:04:39,107 --> 00:04:42,610
Every time, I think I'm gonna wake up
back in the jungle.

6
00:04:48,617 --> 00:04:52,328
When I was home after my first tour,
it was worse.

7
00:05:00,754 --> 00:05:03,255
I'd wake up, and there'd be nothing.

8
00:05:11,263 --> 00:05:15,350
I hardly said a word to my wife
until I said yes to a divorce.

9
00:05:18,479 --> 00:05:21,064
When I was here, I wanted to be there.

10
00:05:22,024 --> 00:05:26,861
When I was there, all I could think of
was getting back into the jungle.

11
00:05:30,241 --> 00:05:32,116
I'm here a week now.

12
00:05:35,704 --> 00:05:37,663
Waiting for a mission.

13
00:05:38,748 --> 00:05:40,290
Getting softer.

14
00:05:45,714 --> 00:05:48,799
Every minute I stay in this room,
I get weaker.

15
00:05:49,259 --> 00:05:51,293
And every minute
Charlie squats in the bush,

16
00:05:51,393 --> 00:05:53,053
he gets stronger.

17
00:05:58,101 --> 00:06:02,020
Each time I looked around,
the walls moved in a little tighter.

18
00:07:41,826 --> 00:07:44,369
Everyone gets everything he wants.

19
00:07:45,412 --> 00:07:47,163
I wanted a mission.

20
00:07:48,123 --> 00:07:50,499
And for my sins, they gave me one.

21
00:07:52,001 --> 00:07:54,419
Brought it up to me like room service.

22
00:07:55,338 --> 00:07:57,756
Captain Willard, are you in there?

23
00:07:58,383 --> 00:08:00,092
Yeah, I'm coming.

24
00:08:00,552 --> 00:08:02,845
It was a real choice mission.

25
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:07,432
And when it was over,
I'd never want another.

26
00:08:16,150 --> 00:08:18,685
- What do you want?
- Are you all right, Captain?

27
00:08:18,785 --> 00:08:20,695
What does it look like?

28
00:08:29,872 --> 00:08:32,615
- Are you Captain Willard, 505th Battalion?
- Affirmative.

29
00:08:32,715 --> 00:08:34,250
- 173rd Airborne?
- Yeah.

30
00:08:34,376 --> 00:08:37,211
- Assigned to SOG?
- Hey, buddy, you gonna shut the door?

31
00:08:39,882 --> 00:08:42,466
We have orders to escort you to the airfield.

32
00:08:45,595 --> 00:08:47,462
- What are the charges?
- Sir?

33
00:08:47,562 --> 00:08:48,562
What'd I do?

34
00:08:49,307 --> 00:08:50,841
There's no charges, Captain.

35
00:08:50,941 --> 00:08:54,853
You have orders to report
to COMSEC Intelligence at Nha Trang.

36
00:08:56,230 --> 00:08:57,931
- I see.
- All right?

37
00:08:58,031 --> 00:09:00,525
- Nha Trang for me?
- That's right.

38
00:09:01,569 --> 00:09:04,154
Come on, Captain. You still have
a few hours to get cleaned up.

39
00:09:04,363 --> 00:09:07,073
- I'm not feeling too good.
- Captain?

40
00:09:09,118 --> 00:09:11,819
Dave, come here and give me a hand.
We got a dead one.

41
00:09:11,919 --> 00:09:14,205
Come on, Captain. Let's take a shower.

42
00:09:14,331 --> 00:09:16,073
- Don't be an ass.
- Get hold of him good.

43
00:09:16,173 --> 00:09:18,326
We're gonna take a shower, Captain.

44
00:09:18,426 --> 00:09:20,502
- In we go.
- Now stand underneath this, Captain.

45
00:09:33,266 --> 00:09:37,602
I was going to the worst place in the world
and I didn't even know it yet.

46
00:09:38,812 --> 00:09:41,598
Weeks away
and hundreds of miles up a river

47
00:09:41,698 --> 00:09:44,684
that snaked through the war
like a main circuit cable,

48
00:09:44,784 --> 00:09:46,811
plugged straight into Kurtz.

49
00:09:46,911 --> 00:09:49,614
Insult me again and I'll kick your ass...

50
00:09:50,241 --> 00:09:52,692
It was no accident
that I got to be the caretaker

51
00:09:52,792 --> 00:09:55,245
of Colonel Walter E. Kurtz's memory

52
00:09:55,704 --> 00:09:58,957
any more than being back in Saigon
was an accident.

53
00:10:00,584 --> 00:10:04,128
There is no way to tell his story
without telling my own.

54
00:10:04,880 --> 00:10:06,872
And if his story is really a confession...

55
00:10:06,972 --> 00:10:08,123
Captain Willard reporting, sir.

56
00:10:08,223 --> 00:10:09,215
...then so is mine.

57
00:10:09,315 --> 00:10:12,511
- Captain. Good. Come on in.
- Thank you, sir.

58
00:10:12,804 --> 00:10:16,223
- Stand at ease.
- General.

59
00:10:18,226 --> 00:10:20,594
Do you want a cigarette?

60
00:10:20,694 --> 00:10:22,437
No, thank you, sir.

61
00:10:23,856 --> 00:10:26,475
Captain, have you ever seen
this gentleman before?

62
00:10:26,575 --> 00:10:27,693
No, sir.

63
00:10:27,986 --> 00:10:30,654
- Met the General or myself?
- No, sir.

64
00:10:30,905 --> 00:10:32,155
Not personally.

65
00:10:33,532 --> 00:10:35,733
You've worked a lot on your own,
haven't you, Captain?

66
00:10:35,833 --> 00:10:36,943
Yes, sir, I have.

67
00:10:37,043 --> 00:10:38,486
Your report specifies Intelligence,

68
00:10:38,586 --> 00:10:40,621
Counterintelligence with COMSEC, I Corps.

69
00:10:41,081 --> 00:10:43,499
I'm not presently disposed
to discuss those operations, sir.

70
00:10:53,218 --> 00:10:55,219
Did you not work for the CIA in I Corps?

71
00:10:57,639 --> 00:10:58,756
No, sir.

72
00:10:58,856 --> 00:11:01,508
Did you not assassinate
a government tax collector,

73
00:11:01,608 --> 00:11:04,311
Quang Tri Province, June 18, 1968?

74
00:11:07,106 --> 00:11:08,356
Captain?

75
00:11:09,942 --> 00:11:14,571
Sir, I am unaware
of any such activity or operation,

76
00:11:16,449 --> 00:11:20,902
nor would I be disposed
to discuss such an operation

77
00:11:21,002 --> 00:11:23,455
if it did, in fact, exist, sir.

78
00:11:35,342 --> 00:11:37,585
I thought we'd have
a bite of lunch while we talk.

79
00:11:37,685 --> 00:11:40,804
I hope you brought
a good appetite, Captain.

80
00:11:41,431 --> 00:11:43,474
I noticed that you have

81
00:11:45,185 --> 00:11:46,894
a bad hand, there. Are you wounded?

82
00:11:47,103 --> 00:11:49,597
I had a little fishing accident on R&R, sir.

83
00:11:49,697 --> 00:11:52,232
- Fishing on R&R?
- Yes, sir.

84
00:11:52,650 --> 00:11:55,060
But you're feeling fit?
You're ready for duty?

85
00:11:55,160 --> 00:11:57,445
Yes, General. Very much so, sir.

86
00:11:57,821 --> 00:11:59,481
Well, let's see what we have here.

87
00:11:59,581 --> 00:12:02,992
Roast beef, and usually it's not bad.

88
00:12:04,787 --> 00:12:07,288
Try some, Jerry, and pass it around.

89
00:12:07,956 --> 00:12:11,042
To save a little time,
we might pass both ways.

90
00:12:14,421 --> 00:12:17,499
Captain, I don't know
how you feel about this shrimp,

91
00:12:17,599 --> 00:12:19,834
but if you'll eat it,

92
00:12:19,934 --> 00:12:23,136
you'll never have to prove your courage
in any other way.

93
00:12:24,180 --> 00:12:27,182
Right, well,
why don't I just take a piece here?

94
00:12:28,101 --> 00:12:31,603
Captain, you've heard
of Colonel Walter E. Kurtz?

95
00:12:34,482 --> 00:12:36,233
Yes, sir, I've heard the name.

96
00:12:37,026 --> 00:12:38,185
Jesus.

97
00:12:38,285 --> 00:12:40,779
Operations officer, Fifth Special Forces.

98
00:12:41,280 --> 00:12:43,941
Luke, would you play that tape
for the Captain, please?

99
00:12:44,041 --> 00:12:47,494
- Yes, sir. I'm sorry, sir.
- Listen to this carefully, Captain.

100
00:12:49,621 --> 00:12:52,706
October 9, 0430 hours,
sector Peter Victor King.

101
00:12:52,833 --> 00:12:54,875
These were monitored out of Cambodia.

102
00:12:56,336 --> 00:12:58,629
This has been verified
as Colonel Kurtz's voice.

103
00:12:58,797 --> 00:13:01,465
I watched a snail

104
00:13:02,968 --> 00:13:04,760
crawl along the edge

105
00:13:05,804 --> 00:13:07,555
of a straight razor.

106
00:13:09,141 --> 00:13:10,766
That's my dream.

107
00:13:12,978 --> 00:13:14,728
It's my nightmare.

108
00:13:17,314 --> 00:13:19,232
Crawling, slithering

109
00:13:20,484 --> 00:13:22,152
along the edge

110
00:13:23,821 --> 00:13:26,990
of a straight razor,

111
00:13:29,243 --> 00:13:30,743
and surviving.

112
00:13:33,497 --> 00:13:38,084
Transmission 11, received '68,
December 30, 0500 hours.

113
00:13:38,335 --> 00:13:40,170
Sector King Zulu King.

114
00:13:41,964 --> 00:13:44,048
But we must kill them.

115
00:13:44,341 --> 00:13:46,341
We must incinerate them,

116
00:13:46,676 --> 00:13:48,177
pig after pig,

117
00:13:49,512 --> 00:13:51,388
cow after cow,

118
00:13:53,308 --> 00:13:55,184
village after village,

119
00:13:55,393 --> 00:13:57,019
army after army.

120
00:13:58,021 --> 00:14:00,314
And they call me an assassin.

121
00:14:00,773 --> 00:14:05,611
What do you call it
when the assassins accuse the assassin?

122
00:14:06,154 --> 00:14:07,404
They lie.

123
00:14:08,198 --> 00:14:10,491
They lie, and we have to be merciful

124
00:14:10,742 --> 00:14:12,700
for those who lie.

125
00:14:13,577 --> 00:14:16,177
Those nabobs,

126
00:14:18,624 --> 00:14:20,249
I hate them.

127
00:14:21,376 --> 00:14:23,127
I do hate them.

128
00:14:28,675 --> 00:14:31,669
Walt Kurtz was one of the most
outstanding officers

129
00:14:31,769 --> 00:14:33,888
this country's ever produced.

130
00:14:34,223 --> 00:14:37,391
He was brilliant.
He was outstanding in every way.

131
00:14:38,227 --> 00:14:40,769
And he was a good man, too.

132
00:14:40,895 --> 00:14:42,771
A humanitarian man.

133
00:14:44,065 --> 00:14:45,899
A man of wit and humor.

134
00:14:47,318 --> 00:14:49,444
He joined the Special Forces.

135
00:14:51,531 --> 00:14:53,323
And after that,

136
00:14:55,326 --> 00:14:58,161
his ideas, methods,

137
00:15:00,665 --> 00:15:01,865
became

138
00:15:04,377 --> 00:15:05,752
unsound.

139
00:15:11,174 --> 00:15:12,774
Unsound.

140
00:15:18,139 --> 00:15:22,718
Now he's crossed into Cambodia
with this Montagnard army of his

141
00:15:22,818 --> 00:15:26,564
that worship the man like a god.

142
00:15:27,274 --> 00:15:30,776
And follow every order, however ridiculous.

143
00:15:32,362 --> 00:15:36,281
Well, I have some other shocking news
to tell you.

144
00:15:37,032 --> 00:15:39,325
Colonel Kurtz is about to be

145
00:15:40,244 --> 00:15:41,995
arrested for murder.

146
00:15:42,955 --> 00:15:45,873
I don't follow, sir. Murdered who?

147
00:15:46,083 --> 00:15:50,003
Kurtz had ordered the execution
of some Vietnamese intelligence agents.

148
00:15:50,296 --> 00:15:52,755
Men he believed were double agents.

149
00:15:54,258 --> 00:15:56,843
So he took matters into his own hands.

150
00:15:59,096 --> 00:16:01,097
Well, you see, Willard,

151
00:16:02,265 --> 00:16:04,266
in this war, things get

152
00:16:05,602 --> 00:16:07,644
confused out there.

153
00:16:08,521 --> 00:16:12,057
Power, ideals, the old morality,

154
00:16:12,157 --> 00:16:14,818
and practical military necessity.

155
00:16:16,821 --> 00:16:19,281
But out there with these natives,

156
00:16:20,450 --> 00:16:23,368
it must be a temptation

157
00:16:25,204 --> 00:16:26,413
to be God.

158
00:16:30,167 --> 00:16:33,377
Because there's a conflict
in every human heart

159
00:16:34,546 --> 00:16:37,340
between the rational and the irrational,

160
00:16:38,175 --> 00:16:40,051
between good and evil.

161
00:16:41,595 --> 00:16:43,929
And good does not always triumph.

162
00:16:46,475 --> 00:16:47,850
Sometimes

163
00:16:49,603 --> 00:16:51,187
the dark side

164
00:16:51,855 --> 00:16:56,233
overcomes what Lincoln called,
"The better angels of our nature."

165
00:16:58,152 --> 00:17:00,570
Every man has got a breaking point.

166
00:17:01,447 --> 00:17:03,198
You and I have them.

167
00:17:04,867 --> 00:17:07,035
Walt Kurtz has reached his,

168
00:17:09,121 --> 00:17:11,748
and very obviously he has gone insane.

169
00:17:25,053 --> 00:17:28,889
Yes, sir. Very much so, sir.
Obviously insane.

170
00:17:33,478 --> 00:17:37,106
Your mission is to proceed
up the Nung River in a Navy patrol boat,

171
00:17:39,067 --> 00:17:41,902
pick up Colonel Kurtz's path at Nu Mung Ba,

172
00:17:42,362 --> 00:17:45,239
follow it, learn what you can
along the way.

173
00:17:45,407 --> 00:17:48,150
When you find the Colonel,
infiltrate his team

174
00:17:48,250 --> 00:17:50,828
by whatever means available

175
00:17:51,704 --> 00:17:53,746
and terminate the Colonel's command.

176
00:18:00,045 --> 00:18:02,463
Terminate the Colonel?

177
00:18:03,757 --> 00:18:07,961
He's out there operating
without any decent restraint,

178
00:18:08,061 --> 00:18:13,766
totally beyond the pale
of any acceptable human conduct.

179
00:18:14,017 --> 00:18:17,103
And he is still in the field,
commanding troops.

180
00:18:18,604 --> 00:18:21,940
Terminate with extreme prejudice.

181
00:18:23,651 --> 00:18:27,112
You understand, Captain,
that this mission does not exist,

182
00:18:28,906 --> 00:18:30,782
nor will it ever exist.

183
00:19:26,003 --> 00:19:28,797
How many people had I already killed?

184
00:19:29,632 --> 00:19:32,801
There were those six
that I knew about for sure.

185
00:19:33,677 --> 00:19:36,846
Close enough to blow their last breath
in my face.

186
00:19:39,183 --> 00:19:44,144
But this time it was an American
and an officer.

187
00:19:55,698 --> 00:20:00,035
That wasn't supposed to make
any difference to me, but it did.

188
00:20:02,664 --> 00:20:06,116
Shit, charging a man with murder
in this place

189
00:20:06,216 --> 00:20:09,794
was like handing out speeding tickets
at the Indy 500.

190
00:20:11,880 --> 00:20:16,050
I took the mission.
What the hell else was I gonna do?

191
00:20:17,928 --> 00:20:21,556
But I really didn't know
what I'd do when I found him.

192
00:20:28,564 --> 00:20:30,898
Did you check the tank?

193
00:20:31,233 --> 00:20:32,233
Yeah.

194
00:20:34,403 --> 00:20:37,904
I was being ferried down the coast
in a Navy PBR.

195
00:20:38,072 --> 00:20:42,367
A type of plastic patrol boat,
a pretty common sight on the rivers.

196
00:20:42,702 --> 00:20:45,070
They said it was a good way
to pick up information and move

197
00:20:45,170 --> 00:20:47,414
without drawing a lot of attention.

198
00:20:47,748 --> 00:20:49,416
And that was okay.

199
00:20:49,625 --> 00:20:51,835
I needed the air and the time.

200
00:20:53,087 --> 00:20:55,080
Only problem was, I wouldn't be alone.

201
00:20:55,180 --> 00:20:57,007
Morning, Captain.

202
00:20:59,385 --> 00:21:02,304
The crew were mostly just kids.

203
00:21:02,722 --> 00:21:05,764
Rock 'n' rollers
with one foot in their graves.

204
00:21:06,808 --> 00:21:09,184
- How old are you?
- Seventeen.

205
00:21:10,729 --> 00:21:13,973
The machinist, the one they called Chef,
was from New Orleans.

206
00:21:14,073 --> 00:21:16,609
He was wrapped too tight for Vietnam.

207
00:21:16,985 --> 00:21:19,445
Probably wrapped too tight
for New Orleans.

208
00:21:19,988 --> 00:21:22,231
Lance, on the forward .50s,
was a famous surfer

209
00:21:22,331 --> 00:21:24,650
from the beaches south of LA.

210
00:21:24,750 --> 00:21:28,370
To look at him, you wouldn't believe
he'd ever fired a weapon in his life.

211
00:21:30,456 --> 00:21:34,826
Clean, Mr. Clean,
was from some South Bronx shithole,

212
00:21:34,926 --> 00:21:36,995
and I think the light and space of Vietnam

213
00:21:37,095 --> 00:21:39,297
really put the zap on his head.

214
00:21:42,259 --> 00:21:44,594
Then there was Phillips, the Chief.

215
00:21:44,720 --> 00:21:48,548
It might have been my mission,
but it sure as shit was the Chief's boat.

216
00:21:48,648 --> 00:21:50,884
There's about two points
where we can draw enough water

217
00:21:50,984 --> 00:21:53,019
to get into the Nung River.

218
00:21:53,395 --> 00:21:55,897
They're both hot, belong to Charlie.

219
00:21:57,524 --> 00:21:59,024
Don't worry about it.

220
00:21:59,859 --> 00:22:01,401
Don't smoke.

221
00:22:03,363 --> 00:22:06,490
You know,
I've pulled a few special ops in here.

222
00:22:06,658 --> 00:22:08,533
About six months ago,

223
00:22:09,160 --> 00:22:12,496
I took a man who was going up
past the bridge at Do Luong.

224
00:22:13,706 --> 00:22:15,666
He was regular Army, too.

225
00:22:18,336 --> 00:22:20,837
I heard he shot himself in the head.

226
00:22:29,721 --> 00:22:33,015
At first, I thought
they handed me the wrong dossier.

227
00:22:33,558 --> 00:22:36,310
I couldn't believe
they wanted this man dead.

228
00:22:38,021 --> 00:22:40,815
Third-generation West Point,
top of his class,

229
00:22:40,982 --> 00:22:46,529
Korea, Airborne,
about 1,000 decorations, et cetera, et cetera.

230
00:22:49,950 --> 00:22:54,202
I had heard his voice on the tape
and it really put the hook in me,

231
00:22:54,912 --> 00:22:58,581
but I couldn't connect up
that voice with this man.

232
00:23:05,673 --> 00:23:08,550
Like they said, he had an impressive career.

233
00:23:09,510 --> 00:23:11,302
Maybe too impressive.

234
00:23:12,388 --> 00:23:13,888
I mean, perfect.

235
00:23:14,932 --> 00:23:18,802
He was being groomed
for one of the top slots in the corporation,

236
00:23:18,902 --> 00:23:21,729
General, Chief of Staff, anything.

237
00:23:24,023 --> 00:23:28,102
In 1964, he returned from a tour
with advisory command in Vietnam

238
00:23:28,202 --> 00:23:30,237
and things started to slip.

239
00:23:30,572 --> 00:23:34,867
His report to the Joint Chiefs of Staff
and Lyndon Johnson was restricted.

240
00:23:37,120 --> 00:23:38,954
Seems they didn't dig
what he had to tell them.

241
00:23:40,749 --> 00:23:43,743
During the next few months,
he made three requests for transfer

242
00:23:43,843 --> 00:23:49,088
to Airborne training, Fort Benning, Georgia,
and was finally accepted.

243
00:23:51,800 --> 00:23:53,259
Airborne?

244
00:23:56,013 --> 00:23:57,764
He was 38 years old.

245
00:23:59,767 --> 00:24:01,934
Why the fuck would he do that?

246
00:24:04,271 --> 00:24:07,565
1966, joins Special Forces,

247
00:24:08,609 --> 00:24:10,067
returns Vietnam.

248
00:24:11,779 --> 00:24:13,813
- Hey, what's that?
- Arc light.

249
00:24:13,913 --> 00:24:16,815
- What's that?
- B-52 strike.

250
00:24:16,915 --> 00:24:17,715
Man.

251
00:24:18,792 --> 00:24:20,152
- What's that?
- Arc light.

252
00:24:20,252 --> 00:24:23,288
I hate that. Every time I hear that,
something terrible happens.

253
00:24:23,414 --> 00:24:25,365
Charlie don't never see them
or hear them, man.

